ry bowel disease; <sup>b </sup>= cellulitis, meningitis, leptospirosis.</p><p>APACHE II = Acute Physiology, Age, and Chronic Health Evaluation II; ICU = intensive care unit; NS = not significant; SOFA = Sequential Organ Failure Assessment.</p></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap></sec><sec><title>The association of the MBL2 gene polymorphisms with sepsis susceptibility</title><p>Patients who were heterozygous (<italic>A/B</italic>) or homozygous (<italic>B/B</italic>) for the polymorphism at codon 54 (adjusted OR, 0.370; 95% CI, 0.207 to 0.661, <italic>P </italic>= 0.001) were less likely to have septic shock in the sepsis group (Table <xref ref-type="table" rid="T2">2</xref>). Those patients in the sepsis group who were heterozygous (<italic>H/L</italic>) or homozygous (<italic>L/L</italic>) at -550 (adjusted OR, 0.476; 95% CI, 0.249 to 0.910, <italic>P </italic>= 0.025) were less likely to have septic shock (Table <xref ref-type="table" rid="T3">3</xref>). The frequencies of <italic>P/Q </italic>at +4 were not significantly different among the three groups (data not shown).</p><table-wrap id="T2" position="float"><label>Table 2</label><caption><p>Genotype frequencies for Gly54Asp in mannose-binding lectin between patients and controls and between septic patients</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="center">Locus</th><th align="center">Allele</th><th align="center" colspan="2">Group<break/>N (%)</th><th align="center" colspan="2">Group<break/>n (%)</th><th align="center">OR<break/>(95% CI)</th><th align="center"><italic>P</italic></th><th align="center">Adjusted OR<sup>a</sup><break/>(95% CI)</th><th align="center"><italic>P</italic></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td/><td/><td align="center" colspan="2">Sepsis</td><td align="center" colspan="2">Control</td><td/><td/><td/><td/></tr><tr><td align="center">GG</td><td align="center">A</td><td align="center">185</td><td align="center">72.27</td><td align="center">262</td><td align="center">66.